I am working with `WindowsAPICodePack` and moving to .Net Standard 2.1. Is there a way to convert` TypeLibType` to .Net Standard?

It currently requires `Microsoft.NetFX20`.

```
using System;
using System.Collections;
using System.Runtime.CompilerServices;
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;

namespace Microsoft.WindowsAPICodePack.Net
{
    [ComImport]
    [TypeLibType(0x1040)]
    [Guid("DCB00002-570F-4A9B-8D69-199FDBA5723B")]
    internal interface INetwork
    { }
}
```

I have .net standard project and my project is running on Linux 
I can see that there is a memory leak problem on the following lines:

using (X509Chain x509Chain = new X509Chain())
{	
	x509Chain.ChainPolicy.RevocationMode = X509RevocationMode.NoCheck;
	x509Chain.ChainPolicy.ExtraStore.AddRange(_trustedStore.ToArray());

	x509Chain.Build(Certificate);

	// Check if the returned errors in the build are acceptable
	if (x509Chain.ChainStatus.Any())
	{
	}
}

When running with a high load, the memory of the process starts at %MEM = 1.1 and after a few hours, the %MEM is  2.0

Any help will be highly appreciated.

```cs
using System;
public unsafe class C {
    public (int a, int b)* F;
    
    public void M(C c)
    {
        _ = c.F->a;
        Console.WriteLine(c.F->a);
    }
}
```

This works when within the same assembly. However, if you attempt to access `F` from a different assembly, we cannot decode the tuple type correctly and report that `F` is not supported by the language. Should be a fairly simple change I'll implement while implementing support for function pointer decoding.

_This issue has been moved from [a ticket on Developer Community](https://developercommunity.visualstudio.com/content/idea/1011650/please-provide-an-option-to-leave-only-braces-on-s.html)._

---
`csharp_preserve_single_line_statements` will keep both

```csharp

string a = ""; int b = 1;


Console.WriteLine(a); Console.WriteLine(b);

```

and

```csharp

if (a) { Console.WriteLine(a); }
```
Whilst many developers like the second form, but discourage the first one. But with this option on it is being formatted to

```c#

if (a)

{ Console.WriteLine(a); }
```

Which is even worse (IMO) than

```csharp

if (a)
{
    Console.WriteLine(a);
}

The title describes the repro which uses `IEnumerable<T>`, but I imagine any generic type would do the same here.

**Version Used**: 

Visual Studio 2019 16.6.0 Preview 5.0
.NET 3.1 console application

**Steps to Reproduce**:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

namespace Repro
{
    public class Numbers
    {
        public int Id { get; set; }
        public List<int> Values { get; set; }
    }

    public class Test
    {
        public void TestMethod()
        {
            var numbers = new Numbers();
            GenericSingle(numbers, g => g.Id);
            GenericMultiple(numbers, g => g.Values);
        }

        public U GenericSingle<T, U>(T item, Func<T, U> getter)
        {
            return getter(item);
        }

        public IEnumerable<U> GenericMultiple<T, U>(T item, Func<T, IEnumerable<U>> getter)
        {
            return getter(item);
        }
    }
}
```

1. Observe that the above code is valid and compiles with no errors.
2. Delete the text `.Id` from the `GenericSingle` invocation, then type `.` to trigger completion.
3. Delete the text `.Values` from the `GenericMultiple` invocation, then type `.` to trigger completion.

**Expected Behavior**:

In both steps 2 and 3, the completion list shows the `Id` and `Values` members of the `Numbers` class.

**Actual Behavior**:

The members only appear in the completion list in step 2.

If the type arguments are specified explicitly, then completion works as expected. If also works as expected if `GenericMultiple` is converted to an extension method as below:

```csharp
public static IEnumerable<U> GenericExtension<T, U>(this T item, Func<T, IEnumerable<U>> getter)
{
    return getter(item);
}

// ...

numbers.GenericExtension(g => g.[||] // completion works here
```

